1
00:00:06,039 --> 00:00:07,440
Here we go.

2
00:00:08,008 --> 00:00:08,875
All right.

3
00:00:10,877 --> 00:00:13,013
Come on in.

4
00:00:14,147 --> 00:00:17,283
- Thank you.
- Hold on a second.

5
00:00:20,820 --> 00:00:22,222
Now, come on in.

6
00:00:25,725 --> 00:00:26,760
Thank you.

7
00:00:27,394 --> 00:00:28,695
Come on, have a seat.

8
00:00:41,341 --> 00:00:42,175
Oh!

9
00:00:44,477 --> 00:00:45,311
There.

10
00:00:51,217 --> 00:00:52,251
Pajamas for you.

11
00:00:52,252 --> 00:00:54,386
It's going to be a long night, right?

12
00:00:54,387 --> 00:00:57,656
I'm all ears, so just relax
and talk to me.

13
00:00:57,657 --> 00:00:58,758
I'll get changed too.

14
00:01:04,898 --> 00:01:05,799
<i>You know what?</i>

15
00:01:06,699 --> 00:01:08,535
I was in a relationship with Oda.

16
00:01:10,336 --> 00:01:13,006
I should have protected him.

17
00:01:18,878 --> 00:01:21,147
Arikeeno, you don't have to tell me

18
00:01:23,550 --> 00:01:24,984
if you don't want to tell me.

19
00:01:29,189 --> 00:01:30,990
I've been wanting to tell you,

20
00:01:33,860 --> 00:01:35,829
because you're the only one I could.

21
00:01:43,169 --> 00:01:45,537
These pajamas are so big.

22
00:01:45,538 --> 00:01:46,573
I know.

23
00:01:47,474 --> 00:01:48,942
Were these your ex-boyfriend's?

24
00:01:49,909 --> 00:01:51,377
No, my current boyfriend's.

25
00:01:52,345 --> 00:01:53,346
What?

26
00:01:54,781 --> 00:01:58,084
I'm just messing with you!
They're just big pajamas.

27
00:02:05,024 --> 00:02:06,492
Is tea okay with you?

28
00:02:06,493 --> 00:02:07,794
Sure, thanks.

29
00:02:10,296 --> 00:02:13,766
Grab a blanket or whatever
you can find around there.

30
00:02:41,327 --> 00:02:42,829
Now, tell me, Arikeeno.

31
00:02:45,365 --> 00:02:49,903
Why did you decide to take the blame

32
00:02:51,771 --> 00:02:52,772
for Sergeant Oda?

33
00:02:56,576 --> 00:02:57,410
No,

34
00:02:58,578 --> 00:03:00,046
I didn't actually take the blame
for what he did.

35
00:03:02,182 --> 00:03:03,550
I just thought

36
00:03:05,118 --> 00:03:06,786
I could be the one
people pointed their fingers at

37
00:03:08,354 --> 00:03:09,589
rather than him.

38
00:03:14,460 --> 00:03:15,862
<i>He always</i>

39
00:03:16,729 --> 00:03:19,332
<i>tried to understand me</i>

40
00:03:20,300 --> 00:03:21,700
<i>and accepted me for who I am.</i>

41
00:03:21,701 --> 00:03:23,970
I'd be fine with quitting the force

42
00:03:24,837 --> 00:03:26,472
if that's what you prefer.

43
00:03:27,640 --> 00:03:28,841
<i>I, on the other hand,</i>

44
00:03:30,109 --> 00:03:31,678
<i>didn't want people to know about us.</i>

45
00:03:44,290 --> 00:03:46,726
I never thought I could hope for marriage

46
00:03:48,595 --> 00:03:52,398
or a future like that in my life at all.

47
00:03:55,034 --> 00:03:56,970
You couldn't hope for a future?

48
00:03:59,706 --> 00:04:00,673
That's why

49
00:04:03,243 --> 00:04:05,645
I wanted to do well
in the police force, at least.

50
00:04:13,686 --> 00:04:14,854
But...

51
00:04:16,422 --> 00:04:17,857
back then,

52
00:04:19,759 --> 00:04:21,327
<i>I totally freaked out.</i>

53
00:04:22,328 --> 00:04:25,164
<i>And I didn't have the courage
to have faith in him.</i>

54
00:04:28,067 --> 00:04:29,302
I think that's why

55
00:04:31,938 --> 00:04:33,473
he didn't tell me.

56
00:04:34,607 --> 00:04:36,276
He couldn't tell me about Agawa.

57
00:04:42,982 --> 00:04:45,084
I bet you mattered so much to him.

58
00:04:47,320 --> 00:04:48,621
Sergeant Oda...

59
00:04:50,256 --> 00:04:52,025
cared about you, too.

60
00:04:55,028 --> 00:04:56,095
I had no regrets

61
00:04:59,332 --> 00:05:01,234
about leaving the police force.

62
00:05:03,536 --> 00:05:06,506
<i>But I was still
going to keep an eye on Agawa.</i>

63
00:05:08,408 --> 00:05:11,644
<i>So that's why you resigned from the force</i>

64
00:05:12,512 --> 00:05:14,681
<i>and became an interpreter.</i>

65
00:05:18,451 --> 00:05:21,120
The only thing left inside me is anger.

66
00:05:23,156 --> 00:05:25,124
I feel nothing but anger
toward Agawa, the police,

67
00:05:27,527 --> 00:05:29,796
and myself for abandoning Oda.

68
00:05:36,636 --> 00:05:38,571
What were you like

69
00:05:40,406 --> 00:05:44,210
when you were with Sergeant Oda?

70
00:05:48,047 --> 00:05:49,015
What was I like?

71
00:05:50,483 --> 00:05:51,784
Were you smiling?

72
00:05:58,725 --> 00:05:59,692
I don't know.

73
00:06:12,805 --> 00:06:14,240
You know what I think?

74
00:06:15,975 --> 00:06:17,176
Let's say

75
00:06:18,444 --> 00:06:23,082
someone disappears from your sight.

76
00:06:25,318 --> 00:06:28,521
But the person remains
inside all the people left behind.

77
00:06:29,989 --> 00:06:34,193
I think pieces of the person
remain behind.

78
00:06:53,546 --> 00:06:57,417
- Good morning.
- Good morning.

79
00:07:00,820 --> 00:07:01,788
Be sure to separate the garbage properly.

80
00:07:02,388 --> 00:07:03,923
All right, I will.

81
00:07:20,273 --> 00:07:22,541
HAVE SOME OF THIS BECAUSE IT'S SO GOOD!

82
00:07:22,542 --> 00:07:25,111
IT'S DOUFUNAO
WITH A DEEP-FRIED BREAD STICK!

83
00:07:39,692 --> 00:07:40,593
It's nice.

84
00:07:53,039 --> 00:07:56,808
Actually, I wanted to learn
more about Sergeant Oda,

85
00:07:56,809 --> 00:07:59,712
so I went through
his and Detective Agawa's records.

86
00:08:00,813 --> 00:08:01,948
And I found out

87
00:08:02,782 --> 00:08:06,085
when they did their last
questioning session together.

88
00:08:06,752 --> 00:08:10,389
It was ten days
before the sergeant passed away.

89
00:08:11,290 --> 00:08:12,491
Ten days before?

90
00:08:12,492 --> 00:08:15,661
That's right. It was just before
that magazine article came out.

91
00:08:17,563 --> 00:08:18,431
And you know

92
00:08:20,099 --> 00:08:23,503
who was being questioned
in the last session?

93
00:08:25,271 --> 00:08:26,739
It was Lin Mengqi.

94
00:08:29,775 --> 00:08:30,676
Really?

95
00:08:32,612 --> 00:08:35,381
I've never seen the recording of it.

96
00:08:36,015 --> 00:08:36,883
That means

97
00:08:37,850 --> 00:08:43,856
Sergeant Oda didn't submit
the footage to Internal Affairs.

98
00:08:44,390 --> 00:08:45,825
He must have kept it.

99
00:08:55,468 --> 00:08:56,302
What?

100
00:08:59,005 --> 00:09:00,740
Good morning, Arikeeno.

101
00:09:06,245 --> 00:09:07,547
That's an amazing bike.

102
00:09:08,581 --> 00:09:12,884
Didn't you tell me you were planning
to borrow a car from the station?

103
00:09:12,885 --> 00:09:16,087
Yeah, but there weren't
any cars available.

104
00:09:16,088 --> 00:09:18,423
So, I got a bike from a friend instead.

105
00:09:18,424 --> 00:09:19,492
Here.

106
00:09:20,760 --> 00:09:23,563
Let's go see the Sergeant's sister.

107
00:09:27,466 --> 00:09:29,467
Why don't you sit in the back?

108
00:09:29,468 --> 00:09:31,737
It's all right. I'll take the handlebars.

109
00:09:32,538 --> 00:09:35,708
No, thanks. I don't feel comfortable
entrusting my life to you.

110
00:09:36,742 --> 00:09:37,944
You are so mean.

111
00:09:45,651 --> 00:09:46,652
Shakuno,

112
00:09:47,653 --> 00:09:49,855
have you found any clues about Volunteer?

113
00:09:50,456 --> 00:09:51,423
I'm afraid not.

114
00:09:51,424 --> 00:09:53,825
So, it was a swing and a miss?

115
00:09:53,826 --> 00:09:56,328
I feel like I'm chasing after smoke.

116
00:09:56,329 --> 00:09:59,397
There are rumors about where they are,
but they move around.

117
00:09:59,398 --> 00:10:03,035
It's like they cover their tracks
with every step they take.

118
00:10:04,437 --> 00:10:05,705
- What's up?
- Hey.

119
00:10:07,640 --> 00:10:11,310
It kind of sounds like that man
over there, doesn't it?

120
00:10:12,011 --> 00:10:15,481
You can sense a deep darkness churning
within him, you know.

121
00:10:21,954 --> 00:10:25,724
By the way, I heard
our division manager is leaving us

122
00:10:25,725 --> 00:10:27,693
to go to headquarters.

123
00:10:28,260 --> 00:10:29,261
Lieutenant Iiyama is?

124
00:10:31,597 --> 00:10:33,666
<i>He'll be leading
the International Division there.</i>

125
00:10:34,333 --> 00:10:36,267
That's amazing. Congratulations.

126
00:10:36,268 --> 00:10:38,169
Thanks. And they told me

127
00:10:38,170 --> 00:10:42,008
I could bring someone
from this division along.

128
00:10:45,678 --> 00:10:48,413
- You mean, me?
- I'm clutching at straws.

129
00:10:48,414 --> 00:10:50,649
- Does that mean I'm--
- No, I mean... You know...

130
00:10:50,650 --> 00:10:52,284
I just want a mighty warrior.

131
00:10:55,221 --> 00:10:56,188
<i>That's great.</i>

132
00:10:57,623 --> 00:10:59,291
You're getting promoted.

133
00:11:01,527 --> 00:11:03,663
I'm not so sure about that.

134
00:11:04,163 --> 00:11:05,264
It definitely is.

135
00:11:06,766 --> 00:11:09,969
And what did you tell him?

136
00:11:13,172 --> 00:11:14,807
I'm still thinking about it.

137
00:11:18,411 --> 00:11:19,612
I am...

138
00:11:20,546 --> 00:11:24,650
I just like the way things are now.

139
00:11:27,920 --> 00:11:30,990
I come across many lives
on the verge of falling apart.

140
00:11:32,892 --> 00:11:35,761
<i>People say I'm just
picking up cases like crumbs.</i>

141
00:11:36,429 --> 00:11:41,000
<i>But when I keep pushing forward
and investigating without giving up,</i>

142
00:11:42,168 --> 00:11:44,403
things eventually turn out for the better.

143
00:11:47,673 --> 00:11:51,644
Working alongside you as a team
of "crumb-picking heroes,"

144
00:11:52,545 --> 00:11:54,914
I've come to understand many new things.

145
00:11:57,550 --> 00:11:59,485
But at headquarters,

146
00:12:00,019 --> 00:12:03,022
all the cases will naturally be
on a larger scale, right?

147
00:12:08,961 --> 00:12:10,495
I guess...

148
00:12:10,496 --> 00:12:13,065
I think you can simply let your heart
guide your decision.

149
00:12:16,736 --> 00:12:20,372
Let my heart guide my decision?

150
00:12:23,242 --> 00:12:26,312
There's nothing wrong
with stepping onto a bigger stage.

151
00:12:27,613 --> 00:12:31,617
And I truly believe you deserve it.

152
00:12:39,658 --> 00:12:40,760
Arikeeno...

153
00:12:44,497 --> 00:12:47,500
- Well, shall we get going?
- Sure.

154
00:12:52,705 --> 00:12:54,640
As far as I know,

155
00:12:55,341 --> 00:12:57,576
you're the finest police officer
out there.

156
00:12:58,711 --> 00:13:02,715
Huh? What did you just say?
I didn't catch that.

157
00:13:03,516 --> 00:13:05,651
What did you just say?

158
00:13:22,935 --> 00:13:23,769
Yes?

159
00:13:25,871 --> 00:13:26,739
Mr. Arikino...?

160
00:13:28,040 --> 00:13:29,542
It's nice to see you.

161
00:13:32,845 --> 00:13:33,879
Here you go.

162
00:13:37,383 --> 00:13:39,717
My brother would be so pleased.

163
00:13:39,718 --> 00:13:40,920
Take your time.

164
00:13:41,754 --> 00:13:43,189
- Thank you so much.
- Thank you.

165
00:13:48,594 --> 00:13:49,428
Here.

166
00:14:05,277 --> 00:14:06,946
This is the lighter I gave him.

167
00:14:07,813 --> 00:14:09,348
Oh, it is?

168
00:14:10,716 --> 00:14:11,584
Hmm?

169
00:14:14,220 --> 00:14:15,354
It's cleaned up.

170
00:14:27,600 --> 00:14:28,901
It's an SD card.

171
00:14:48,988 --> 00:14:50,389
<i>Well...</i>

172
00:14:51,624 --> 00:14:52,490
Is that Agawa?

173
00:14:52,491 --> 00:14:53,993
<i>So, it's Lin Mengqi.</i>

174
00:14:54,927 --> 00:14:55,761
I was right.

175
00:14:57,496 --> 00:14:59,365
<i>Sergeant Oda had kept this.</i>

176
00:15:32,298 --> 00:15:34,600
Arikeeno, what did she just say?

177
00:15:38,671 --> 00:15:39,805
Arikeeno?

178
00:15:43,175 --> 00:15:44,109
Come in.

179
00:15:48,147 --> 00:15:49,315
What's the matter?

180
00:16:15,040 --> 00:16:15,874
What's the matter?

181
00:16:19,144 --> 00:16:20,746
"Here we are again."

182
00:16:21,947 --> 00:16:23,449
"You're here quite often."

183
00:16:25,017 --> 00:16:27,219
"I don't want to be here."

184
00:16:30,055 --> 00:16:32,458
"Get me out quickly, just like last time."

185
00:16:33,959 --> 00:16:36,562
Unfortunately, it's not that simple.

186
00:16:38,697 --> 00:16:42,935
Officer Oda over there doesn't
understand our language, right?

187
00:16:46,338 --> 00:16:47,639
I know something, you know.

188
00:16:48,407 --> 00:16:50,676
I know what you're doing with him.

189
00:16:53,479 --> 00:16:54,713
What are you talking about?

190
00:16:56,548 --> 00:16:58,249
Look at your face.

191
00:16:58,250 --> 00:17:00,753
Didn't you know
what you were getting into?

192
00:17:03,822 --> 00:17:07,926
You release illegal residents
caught by the police

193
00:17:09,261 --> 00:17:13,699
and sell them to him, telling them
you have a nice job to offer them.

194
00:17:15,167 --> 00:17:18,337
How many people have you sold so far?

195
00:17:18,904 --> 00:17:21,140
Ten? Or maybe twenty?

196
00:17:21,774 --> 00:17:22,841
You sold them to Volunteer.

197
00:17:25,477 --> 00:17:26,545
"To Volunteer."

198
00:17:34,286 --> 00:17:36,655
<i>"What a conniving,
murderous police officer!"</i>

199
00:17:40,159 --> 00:17:42,294
"If you don't want me to expose you,
get me out."

200
00:17:50,069 --> 00:17:51,703
<i>I discovered the footage</i>

201
00:17:52,905 --> 00:17:54,306
<i>Sergeant Oda had been holding onto.</i>

202
00:17:59,711 --> 00:18:03,649
It's the footage he secretly filmed
ten days before he died,

203
00:18:05,017 --> 00:18:07,086
of Lin Mengqi's questioning session.

204
00:18:12,391 --> 00:18:14,393
It's definitive evidence.

205
00:18:23,669 --> 00:18:27,906
It shows you were connected to Volunteer.

206
00:18:31,610 --> 00:18:34,012
You had already suspected it, hadn't you?

207
00:18:43,422 --> 00:18:44,790
But still,

208
00:18:47,493 --> 00:18:49,328
I wanted to believe you were innocent.

209
00:18:57,269 --> 00:18:58,537
And I believe

210
00:18:59,771 --> 00:19:01,173
Sergeant Oda felt the same.

211
00:19:04,610 --> 00:19:08,747
Please, just come clean.

212
00:19:16,855 --> 00:19:20,859
So, this day has finally come.

213
00:19:24,363 --> 00:19:26,064
I knew it was only a matter of time.

214
00:19:29,801 --> 00:19:30,836
Greenhead,

215
00:19:33,272 --> 00:19:34,907
I knew it from the moment I met you.

216
00:19:45,517 --> 00:19:47,085
This country has so many people

217
00:19:49,855 --> 00:19:54,193
who can't express
what they want to say or need.

218
00:19:55,761 --> 00:19:58,830
And a lot of them
face serious difficulties.

219
00:20:04,203 --> 00:20:06,405
I know I don't sound convincing
at this point,

220
00:20:07,139 --> 00:20:09,708
but I really wanted to save
people like them.

221
00:20:10,642 --> 00:20:13,111
That's why I joined
the International Investigation.

222
00:20:15,948 --> 00:20:17,316
If that's true, why would you...?

223
00:20:21,853 --> 00:20:26,592
I wanted to understand
the darkness that entraps them.

224
00:20:33,332 --> 00:20:35,100
I threw myself into it,

225
00:20:36,068 --> 00:20:37,903
determined to understand them.

226
00:20:41,707 --> 00:20:43,241
As a result,

227
00:20:43,242 --> 00:20:46,178
I even obtained information
that other detectives never could.

228
00:20:47,579 --> 00:20:49,081
Before I knew it,

229
00:20:51,183 --> 00:20:53,385
I no longer cared about how I got results.

230
00:20:56,788 --> 00:20:58,757
I handed over money,

231
00:21:00,259 --> 00:21:01,893
and I even handed over people.

232
00:21:04,463 --> 00:21:08,200
I didn't even bother imagining

233
00:21:09,901 --> 00:21:12,204
what would happen to them in the future.

234
00:21:27,352 --> 00:21:28,420
Forgive me.

235
00:21:48,540 --> 00:21:49,374
That's right.

236
00:21:49,875 --> 00:21:51,677
I'm certain this time.

237
00:21:52,678 --> 00:21:53,512
Yes.

238
00:21:55,847 --> 00:21:58,383
Go ahead and issue
a summoning order, please.

239
00:22:00,052 --> 00:22:01,453
Thank you.

240
00:22:24,009 --> 00:22:25,543
Good morning, Miss Koda.

241
00:22:25,544 --> 00:22:27,145
- Good morning.
- Morning.

242
00:22:33,251 --> 00:22:34,986
TO MARI KODA

243
00:22:39,958 --> 00:22:42,160
FROM HIROYA AGAWA

244
00:23:01,279 --> 00:23:02,114
Hey!

245
00:23:02,714 --> 00:23:04,416
<i>Dear Mari Koda...</i>

246
00:23:06,418 --> 00:23:07,486
<i>Here in this letter,</i>

247
00:23:08,387 --> 00:23:12,224
<i>I make my confession.</i>

248
00:23:14,459 --> 00:23:17,229
<i>By the time you read this,</i>

249
00:23:18,263 --> 00:23:23,135
<i>Internal Affairs will have
already issued my summons.</i>

250
00:23:24,970 --> 00:23:29,040
<i>When I got transferred to this division
at Higashi Shinjuku Police Station,</i>

251
00:23:29,574 --> 00:23:34,479
<i>I knew it was my last opportunity
for a fresh start.</i>

252
00:23:38,049 --> 00:23:38,884
<i>But then,</i>

253
00:23:39,651 --> 00:23:43,054
<i>I discovered
that you were investigating Volunteer.</i>

254
00:23:43,889 --> 00:23:45,056
<i>In the end,</i>

255
00:23:45,724 --> 00:23:50,529
<i>I realized I couldn't escape
my wrongdoing.</i>

256
00:23:52,164 --> 00:23:54,099
So, you're Mr. Agawa.

257
00:23:57,869 --> 00:24:01,705
When you catch illegal residents
in adult entertainment venue raids,

258
00:24:01,706 --> 00:24:04,009
give them to me
before you notify immigration.

259
00:24:05,377 --> 00:24:08,313
I need illegal residents
who can help me with my work.

260
00:24:12,484 --> 00:24:14,085
Why are you asking me?

261
00:24:17,556 --> 00:24:20,558
Because you're fluent in Chinese,

262
00:24:20,559 --> 00:24:22,694
you can speak to them directly
when they're arrested.

263
00:24:28,300 --> 00:24:29,800
Most illegal residents

264
00:24:29,801 --> 00:24:33,205
are simply trying to earn money
for their families back home.

265
00:24:35,140 --> 00:24:37,042
This is about helping people.

266
00:24:37,642 --> 00:24:41,146
Turning a blind eye to some
wouldn't affect Japan's public order.

267
00:24:42,180 --> 00:24:45,583
I just need you to have the women state
that they have Japanese husbands.

268
00:24:45,584 --> 00:24:47,385
That's all.

269
00:24:50,455 --> 00:24:51,590
I'm sorry,

270
00:24:52,157 --> 00:24:53,225
but I can't cooperate.

271
00:24:56,394 --> 00:24:57,929
Are you sure about that?

272
00:24:59,865 --> 00:25:04,169
We have an underground network
that links Tokyo to the mainland.

273
00:25:06,771 --> 00:25:08,439
To someone like you,

274
00:25:08,440 --> 00:25:11,977
who seeks a safer society for Japan,
we can give the information you want.

275
00:25:33,331 --> 00:25:38,369
<i>The total number of illegal residents
I handed over to Volunteer</i>

276
00:25:38,370 --> 00:25:39,704
<i>was 47.</i>

277
00:25:41,806 --> 00:25:44,543
<i>It was no different
from sentencing them to death.</i>

278
00:25:46,411 --> 00:25:48,747
<i>And... one more person.</i>

279
00:25:51,950 --> 00:25:53,517
I'm going ahead then.

280
00:25:53,518 --> 00:25:54,586
Hey, just a thought.

281
00:25:55,387 --> 00:25:58,188
I'll grab something nice on the way home.
Let's eat together.

282
00:25:58,189 --> 00:25:59,858
Something nice? Like what?

283
00:26:01,660 --> 00:26:02,993
How about some chicken?

284
00:26:02,994 --> 00:26:03,995
That'll be great.

285
00:26:04,663 --> 00:26:05,830
All right, then.

286
00:26:16,641 --> 00:26:21,613
<i>I threatened Sergeant Satoru Oda.</i>

287
00:26:22,213 --> 00:26:26,318
Back then,
what were you discussing with Lin Mengqi?

288
00:26:30,822 --> 00:26:34,125
Because I wanted to hear the truth
directly from you,

289
00:26:35,460 --> 00:26:37,162
I chose not to release that data.

290
00:26:37,729 --> 00:26:40,197
If you keep insisting that you're going

291
00:26:40,198 --> 00:26:43,535
to make that data public no matter what...

292
00:26:54,779 --> 00:26:56,848
I'll expose your secret completely.

293
00:26:59,417 --> 00:27:03,021
I wonder what people in the force
will think about you

294
00:27:04,222 --> 00:27:05,490
if they learn about you two.

295
00:27:19,437 --> 00:27:21,206
<i>I had no idea</i>

296
00:27:21,973 --> 00:27:25,677
<i>how much my actions
would consume Sergeant Oda.</i>

297
00:27:26,945 --> 00:27:28,546
<i>I didn't even care to imagine it.</i>

298
00:27:30,915 --> 00:27:34,919
<i>I think Sergeant Oda made that choice</i>

299
00:27:35,887 --> 00:27:40,025
<i>to protect the person
he cared about the most.</i>

300
00:27:40,859 --> 00:27:42,827
<i>I really believe so.</i>

301
00:27:48,333 --> 00:27:50,201
<i>I know I'm being selfish,</i>

302
00:27:51,703 --> 00:27:55,673
<i>but I've been in agony, carrying
this guilt in my heart all this time.</i>

303
00:27:55,674 --> 00:27:58,743
<i>It's been painful to go on living.</i>

304
00:28:03,748 --> 00:28:04,582
<i>Now,</i>

305
00:28:05,984 --> 00:28:07,886
<i>I want to be free.</i>

306
00:28:10,622 --> 00:28:12,590
<i>Both Volunteer and I</i>

307
00:28:14,159 --> 00:28:15,827
<i>will face the punishment we deserve.</i>

308
00:28:23,401 --> 00:28:25,469
<i>Our station is mobilizing to make arrests.</i>

309
00:28:25,470 --> 00:28:27,705
Arrests? You mean right now?

310
00:28:27,706 --> 00:28:29,807
At ten pm, Volunteer is meeting his men

311
00:28:29,808 --> 00:28:31,876
in a multi-tenant building in Shin-Okubo.

312
00:28:32,610 --> 00:28:34,278
There will be about four of them.

313
00:28:34,279 --> 00:28:36,346
Tarao, take command of the arrests.

314
00:28:36,347 --> 00:28:39,450
We're moving on Volunteer now?
Don't you think it's too early?

315
00:28:39,451 --> 00:28:41,251
Where did you get this intel?

316
00:28:41,252 --> 00:28:44,489
From Detective Agawa.
He just gave it to me this morning.

317
00:28:52,397 --> 00:28:53,998
- Mr. Shack?
- <i>Where the heck are you?</i>

318
00:28:54,933 --> 00:28:58,036
<i>Detective Agawa supplied us
with intel on Volunteer's meeting spot.</i>

319
00:29:33,438 --> 00:29:34,472
Listen.

320
00:29:36,407 --> 00:29:38,009
Why don't we call it quits,

321
00:29:38,510 --> 00:29:39,677
Volunteer?

322
00:29:46,684 --> 00:29:48,019
I'm just so disappointed.

323
00:30:00,632 --> 00:30:05,336
I thought that, at the very least,
you were just like us.

324
00:30:11,976 --> 00:30:12,977
Agawa!

325
00:30:14,078 --> 00:30:14,979
Koda...

326
00:31:00,592 --> 00:31:02,727
It's all right.

327
00:31:04,562 --> 00:31:05,396
No, it's not.

328
00:31:09,467 --> 00:31:10,702
It's really all right.

329
00:31:12,503 --> 00:31:13,705
No, it's not!

330
00:31:15,773 --> 00:31:17,208
Detective Agawa!

331
00:31:21,212 --> 00:31:22,480
Detective Agawa!

332
00:31:27,318 --> 00:31:28,386
Detective Agawa!

333
00:31:30,355 --> 00:31:31,456
Detective Agawa!

334
00:31:35,393 --> 00:31:36,361
Agawa!

335
00:31:55,446 --> 00:31:56,547
Miss Koda.

336
00:33:26,371 --> 00:33:29,407
He's lost a lot of blood,
and it's unclear if he'll wake up.

337
00:33:30,341 --> 00:33:32,642
The fact that he's still alive
is unbelievable.

338
00:33:32,643 --> 00:33:34,846
How did he survive a laceration
that serious?

339
00:33:35,346 --> 00:33:36,481
It's all thanks to Koda.

340
00:33:37,081 --> 00:33:39,484
She inserted her fingers into his wound

341
00:33:40,051 --> 00:33:43,354
to stop the bleeding
by compressing his artery.

342
00:33:45,723 --> 00:33:47,091
She did?

343
00:34:05,276 --> 00:34:06,878
Hey, it's been a while.

344
00:34:11,249 --> 00:34:12,083
Do you know him?

345
00:34:25,129 --> 00:34:26,330
"Come on, don't be so cold.

346
00:34:27,632 --> 00:34:29,634
Is Agawa dead?"

347
00:34:45,983 --> 00:34:47,051
Are you the...

348
00:34:48,453 --> 00:34:49,454
Are you Volunteer?

349
00:34:57,328 --> 00:35:00,164
I'm one of many Volunteers.

350
00:35:04,435 --> 00:35:05,436
Do you understand

351
00:35:06,137 --> 00:35:08,305
what you're guilty of?

352
00:35:08,306 --> 00:35:09,640
What about you guys?

353
00:35:11,008 --> 00:35:11,976
What about us?

354
00:35:14,479 --> 00:35:16,380
You guys kept on living,

355
00:35:18,649 --> 00:35:21,018
ignoring people like me, didn't you?

356
00:35:25,389 --> 00:35:28,126
We were just cast into this world
and left behind.

357
00:35:33,965 --> 00:35:35,900
We only deserved pity.

358
00:35:43,941 --> 00:35:45,676
<i>There are so many of us.</i>

359
00:35:47,011 --> 00:35:49,046
<i>There are plenty of others besides me</i>

360
00:35:51,549 --> 00:35:53,084
<i>living in this town.</i>

361
00:36:02,560 --> 00:36:04,061
You understand that, don't you?

362
00:36:11,435 --> 00:36:14,305
It's absolutely impossible
to find every one of us.

363
00:36:20,478 --> 00:36:21,979
You may say it's impossible.

364
00:36:27,251 --> 00:36:28,986
But no matter how many there are,

365
00:36:30,254 --> 00:36:32,056
we will not stop pursuing them.

366
00:36:36,127 --> 00:36:37,862
We're determined to do that.

367
00:37:22,206 --> 00:37:23,441
Detective Agawa,

368
00:37:26,944 --> 00:37:28,980
I won't forgive you.

369
00:37:32,683 --> 00:37:33,985
Think about what you did

370
00:37:36,621 --> 00:37:39,023
to Sergeant Oda
and to so many foreign residents.

371
00:37:41,926 --> 00:37:43,394
You thought you could bring closure

372
00:37:45,696 --> 00:37:47,698
to all of it with just that letter?

373
00:37:52,770 --> 00:37:54,772
There's much more left for you to do.

374
00:37:57,508 --> 00:37:59,877
So, hurry up and wake up.

375
00:38:05,816 --> 00:38:07,118
I'm waiting for you.

376
00:38:18,796 --> 00:38:21,732
This is a confession statement
from Lieutenant Agawa.

377
00:38:26,137 --> 00:38:30,040
It describes how he misinterpreted
in the questioning sessions

378
00:38:30,041 --> 00:38:32,777
and how he was involved with Volunteer.

379
00:38:40,284 --> 00:38:41,585
Are you going to disclose

380
00:38:44,288 --> 00:38:46,090
about the two with anyone else?

381
00:38:51,962 --> 00:38:54,832
Internal Affairs is focusing
on the corrupt connection

382
00:38:55,366 --> 00:38:59,003
between Agawa
and the non-Japanese criminal, Volunteer.

383
00:39:00,304 --> 00:39:03,541
What he had with his colleague personally
is none of our business.

384
00:39:11,849 --> 00:39:13,084
This will be under my charge

385
00:39:15,252 --> 00:39:17,355
and responsibility from now on.

386
00:39:20,324 --> 00:39:22,326
It will never be revealed to the public.

387
00:39:31,369 --> 00:39:34,170
Has Volunteer revealed anything yet?

388
00:39:34,171 --> 00:39:37,741
He has remained completely silent
regarding the case.

389
00:39:37,742 --> 00:39:39,442
I see.

390
00:39:39,443 --> 00:39:40,777
The knife wound on Lin Mengqi's neck

391
00:39:40,778 --> 00:39:43,747
matched the knife he used to attack Agawa.

392
00:39:43,748 --> 00:39:46,816
If he's a professional killer,
he probably won't confess.

393
00:39:46,817 --> 00:39:49,652
I totally agree with you.

394
00:39:49,653 --> 00:39:52,222
But now we're certain
that a human trafficking ring

395
00:39:52,223 --> 00:39:55,458
named Volunteer is operating within Japan.

396
00:39:55,459 --> 00:39:59,295
This will keep the International Division
at headquarters very busy.

397
00:39:59,296 --> 00:40:00,297
I know.

398
00:40:00,931 --> 00:40:04,401
It's too bad you're getting transferred
at a crazy time like this.

399
00:40:04,402 --> 00:40:05,603
I know.

400
00:40:06,470 --> 00:40:07,637
It makes me realize

401
00:40:07,638 --> 00:40:10,508
just how crucial it is
to have brilliant personnel.

402
00:40:15,279 --> 00:40:17,380
Hello, everyone.

403
00:40:17,381 --> 00:40:18,615
Miss Koda!

404
00:40:18,616 --> 00:40:19,549
It's good to see you.

405
00:40:19,550 --> 00:40:23,153
I've brought <i>banh mi</i> sandwiches
for all of you to show my gratitude.

406
00:40:23,154 --> 00:40:25,522
Thank you so much.

407
00:40:25,523 --> 00:40:28,491
Thank you so much for your help
with witness interviews.

408
00:40:28,492 --> 00:40:30,093
You all worked very hard.

409
00:40:30,094 --> 00:40:31,295
Don't even mention it.

410
00:40:31,962 --> 00:40:33,731
The real work begins after this.

411
00:40:34,465 --> 00:40:37,267
Volunteer operates
as a multinational organization.

412
00:40:37,268 --> 00:40:40,437
There will be more instances
where interpreters will be needed.

413
00:40:40,438 --> 00:40:41,772
We need to brace ourselves.

414
00:40:43,574 --> 00:40:44,674
Yes, sir!

415
00:40:44,675 --> 00:40:47,344
You're incredibly inspiring.

416
00:40:48,345 --> 00:40:49,180
Here you go.

417
00:40:50,314 --> 00:40:54,284
You know what? He has changed. Very cool.

418
00:40:54,285 --> 00:40:55,552
- He is, isn't he?
- Thanks for the food.

419
00:40:55,553 --> 00:40:58,455
I knew right from the beginning
how cool he was.

420
00:40:58,456 --> 00:40:59,623
Let's eat.

421
00:41:00,257 --> 00:41:02,493
- Yes, let's do.
- This looks so good.

422
00:41:10,634 --> 00:41:13,904
Please, everyone,
come and help yourselves.

423
00:41:24,648 --> 00:41:27,384
ODA FAMILY GRAVE

424
00:41:31,822 --> 00:41:33,491
I was going to quit

425
00:41:34,258 --> 00:41:36,460
being an interpreter
once everything was resolved.

426
00:41:39,763 --> 00:41:40,764
But now,

427
00:41:41,599 --> 00:41:44,068
there's someone I want to help.

428
00:41:45,336 --> 00:41:46,871
So I'll continue for a bit longer.

429
00:41:49,006 --> 00:41:50,241
Is that all right with you?

430
00:42:02,786 --> 00:42:03,787
Satoru,

431
00:42:06,123 --> 00:42:07,124
thank you.

432
00:42:23,307 --> 00:42:24,341
<i>Eonni,</i>

433
00:42:26,410 --> 00:42:27,845
I've made up my mind.

434
00:42:41,091 --> 00:42:44,395
SIX MONTHS LATER

435
00:42:44,895 --> 00:42:46,229
I'm so late!

436
00:42:46,230 --> 00:42:47,331
Alas!

437
00:42:59,910 --> 00:43:00,743
Arikeeno?

438
00:43:00,744 --> 00:43:03,247
What the heck are you doing?

439
00:43:03,814 --> 00:43:07,283
- Thank you!
- No problem.

440
00:43:07,284 --> 00:43:11,220
"What the heck are you doing?" is my line.
What's going on?

441
00:43:11,221 --> 00:43:14,691
I came to check on you so you
wouldn't be late on your first day.

442
00:43:14,692 --> 00:43:16,960
Aww, thanks!

443
00:43:16,961 --> 00:43:18,028
Come on, let's go.

444
00:43:19,330 --> 00:43:20,463
Good morning, everyone.

445
00:43:20,464 --> 00:43:22,065
Good morning.

446
00:43:22,066 --> 00:43:23,466
Good morning, everyone.

447
00:43:23,467 --> 00:43:25,301
Hang on a second, Arikeeno.

448
00:43:25,302 --> 00:43:26,804
Just a moment.

449
00:43:28,472 --> 00:43:32,076
This is my new business card.

450
00:43:34,244 --> 00:43:37,046
MARI KODA
TOKYO METROPOLITAN PD

451
00:43:37,047 --> 00:43:39,215
You sneered like
a cartoon character again.

452
00:43:39,216 --> 00:43:40,117
I never thought

453
00:43:41,752 --> 00:43:43,354
we'd end up at the same workplace.

454
00:43:45,055 --> 00:43:48,291
I know. We are, uh... you know...

455
00:43:48,292 --> 00:43:49,759
What was it?

456
00:43:49,760 --> 00:43:51,995
- What is it?
- I forgot.

457
00:43:51,996 --> 00:43:55,098
There was this Chinese expression
that Auntie Ma told me.

458
00:43:55,099 --> 00:43:56,833
It's something like "a perfect couple."

459
00:43:56,834 --> 00:43:58,234
- A couple?
- Yeah.

460
00:43:58,235 --> 00:44:01,137
Like "a wise man and a beautiful woman..."

461
00:44:01,138 --> 00:44:02,038
Something like that.

462
00:44:02,039 --> 00:44:03,540
<i>Lang cai nu mao!</i>

463
00:44:04,108 --> 00:44:06,476
<i>Lang cai nu mao!</i>

464
00:44:06,477 --> 00:44:07,778
That's it.

465
00:44:08,512 --> 00:44:09,345
I'm off to work then.

466
00:44:09,346 --> 00:44:11,382
- See you.
- Bye.

467
00:44:12,016 --> 00:44:13,617
- That was it.
- Bye.

468
00:44:15,219 --> 00:44:16,586
How are you feeling

469
00:44:16,587 --> 00:44:18,522
on your first day at work?

470
00:44:19,857 --> 00:44:21,091
Well... I'm very excited.

471
00:44:22,960 --> 00:44:24,427
And how about you?

472
00:44:24,428 --> 00:44:26,829
I feel the same as always.

473
00:44:26,830 --> 00:44:28,932
That's so typical of you.
